{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627453"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:49:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:49:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17122"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17122"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.05,0.02,0.02,0.9]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9812"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68654"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9812"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17122"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54111"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5030"},{"type":"tags","id":"7603"},{"type":"tags","id":"9882"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23021"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68654"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIsosorbide dinitrate is commonly prescribed for patients with angina pectoris and heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of isosorbide dinitrate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibition of angiotensin converting enzyme","Stimulation of prostacyclin synthesis","Direct stimulation of beta-2 adrenergic receptors","Blocks calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle","Conversion to nitric oxide causing vasodilation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of isosorbide dinitrate involves its \u003Cstrong\u003Econversion to nitric oxide causing vasodilation\u003C/strong\u003E. Nitric oxide activates guanylate cyclase, increasing cyclic guanosine monophosphate levels in vascular smooth muscle, leading to relaxation and vasodilation. This predominantly affects venous vessels, reducing preload and cardiac work.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of angiotensin converting enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with ACE inhibitors such as enalapril, which reduce blood pressure by preventing formation of angiotensin II.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of prostacyclin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant mechanism for organic nitrates, though prostacyclin is an endogenous vasodilator.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect stimulation of beta-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism by which medicines like salbutamol cause bronchodilation and vasodilation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of calcium channel blockers such as amlodipine, which reduce vascular tone.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIsosorbide dinitrate undergoes significant first-pass metabolism in the liver, reducing its oral bioavailability. Its vasodilatory effects make it useful in treating angina by reducing cardiac workload and improving myocardial oxygen supply-demand balance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Isosorbide dinitrate is converted to nitric oxide which causes vasodilation through increased cyclic guanosine monophosphate.","Organic nitrates primarily dilate venous vessels, reducing preload and cardiac workload.","First-pass metabolism significantly reduces oral bioavailability of isosorbide dinitrate."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54111"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17122"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54111"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T09:04:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T09:05:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9812"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68654"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Reme